\begin_layout Title
Divisor Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Define and explore the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

divisor operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Its a variant of the Redheffer matrix.
 It is not a bounded operator on 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 It can be used to model the integers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This reviews low-grade ideas surrounding something that I want to call the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

divisor operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Why this is interesting: the divisor operator, as defined below, includes
 the Riemann zeros as part of it's kernel.
 It is a variation on a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Redheffer matrix
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (see Wikipedia).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Dirichlet convolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $f(n)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(n)$
\end_inset

 arithmetic sequences.
 Define Dirichlet convolution as usual:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(f*g\right)\left(n\right)=\sum_{d|n}f\left(d\right)g\left(\frac{n}{d}\right)
\]

\end_inset

This is commutative, associative, Abelian, so its a form of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

addition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 There is a concept of zero.
 The zero is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon\left(n\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{if }n=1\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f*\varepsilon\right)=\left(\varepsilon*f\right)=f$
\end_inset

.
 It is conventional to define the one-unit as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathit{1}\left(n\right)=1\quad\mbox{for all }n
\]

\end_inset

Define the Mobius 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 arithmetic sequence as minus-one, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu*\mathit{1}=\varepsilon
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As such, Dirichlet convolution, together with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{1}$
\end_inset

 can be used to create a model of arithmetic.
 The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

model
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used here in the model-theoretic sense.
 A model of arithmetic is a mapping from the axioms of arithmetic (together
 with the logical connectives and other parts of first-order logic, 
\emph on
e.g.

\emph default
 the tautologies) to the space of countably-infinite sequences.
 As a model, it contains 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nothing more
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 than arithmetic; yet, because the space of countably-infinite sequences
 is much richer than the set of natural numbers, it suggests ways in which
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ordinary arithmetic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be extended in unusual ways.
 The reader is encouraged to loosely envision Cohen's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

forcing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as an inspiration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be precise, there are two models: the structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(*,\varepsilon,\mathit{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 provides a model for the non-negative integers under addition
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(*,\mu,\varepsilon,\mathit{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 is an extension that provides a model for all of the integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}=\left(+,-1,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is understood to stand for the first-order language 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\mathbb{Z}}$
\end_inset

 of expressions obtained from these operators and constants, together with
 equality as a relation.
 As usual, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

less than
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

 provides a total order on the integers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Conjecture*
The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

 on the integers embeds into the lexicographic ordering of strings.
\end_layout

