 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the standard-notation basis vector: i.e.
 all zero's except for a 1 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th location.
 The first vector is 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1}=e_{1}$
\end_inset

, which spans a one-dimensional space.
 Other representatative elements of the affine space can be decomposed as
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{n}=\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{nk}e_{k}
\]

\end_inset

with various constraints applied to the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{nk}$
\end_inset

 to be discovered.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proceeding as before, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{2}=\left(a,1,0,\cdots\right)=a\varepsilon_{1}+e_{2}$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(D-I\right)\varepsilon_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 one may as well take 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{2}$
\end_inset

 to be othogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

, and normalized, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{2}=e_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The second affine space is generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{2}$
\end_inset

 and spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next is 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{3}=\left(b,c,1-c,0,\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Asking for orthogonality to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

 sets 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly the third space is generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{3}=e_{3}$
\end_inset

 and spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before, one may write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{4}=\left(c,d,a-d-1,1,0,\cdots\right)$
