\begin_layout Section*
Spectra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}=\left(s_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 be the vector given by vector components 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{n}=n^{-s}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\zeta}=D\vec{s}$
\end_inset

, then the vector components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\zeta}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{k}=k^{-s}\zeta\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This can be easily seen by inspecting the visual form of the 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 The top row corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 and clearly sums all terms.
 The second row, for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

, sums only even terms, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This demonstrates that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\zeta}$
\end_inset

 is just a constant multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}$
\end_inset

, the constant of proportionality given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In formulas: 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\zeta}=D\vec{s}=\zeta\left(s\right)\vec{s}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a diagonalization, and eigenvector-eigenvalue equation.
 We've written down at least some of the spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar identity holds for any completely multiplicative sequence.
 That is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(mn\right)=f\left(m\right)f\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 for all integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

 then writing 
\begin_inset Formula $g=Df$
\end_inset

 one has that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(1\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}f\left(n\right)\quad\mbox{and}\quad g\left(k\right)=f\left(k\right)g\left(1\right)
\]

\end_inset

which is obviously a formal series when the summation does not numerically
 converge.
 This too has the form of an eigenvalue equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Df=g\left(1\right)f
\]

\end_inset

and provides a spectrum whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 is actually summable and convergent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that a completely multiplicative sequence is determined entirely by
 it's values on the prime numbers: that is, by the values 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 prime.
 It would appear that we've demonstrated a lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be the space of completely multiplicative sequences.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 be the Banach space of summable sequences.
 The the space 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cap\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 lies within the eigenspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I suspect the converse is true, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cap\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 is exactly the eigenspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, but am too lazy to think of a proof right now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Spectral Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of this section is to describe the spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 It's a slow walk through the standard vocabulary and definitions of spectral
 decompositions, mostly posing questions but leaving them unanswered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lets assume (for now) that 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is a bounded operator on the Banach space 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Actually, it isn't bounded, as shown in the next section.
 Reviewing common definitions for bounded operators:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The set of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(D-\lambda I\right):\ell_{1}\to\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one and onto is called the resolvent set, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(D\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It seems that perhaps the resolvent is the empty set in this case (or perhaps,
 per Picard theorem, contains a single point.
 Or two.).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The complement of the resolvent set is the spectrum, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\left(D\right)=\mathbb{C}\backslash\rho\left(\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What kind of spectra are there?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The point spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 are all those values 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\sigma\left(D\right)$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $D-\lambda I$
\end_inset

 is not one-to-one.
 That is, the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $D-\lambda I$
\end_inset

 is non-trivial; 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 there is a vector, other than the zero vector, that is in the kernel of
 
\begin_inset Formula $D-\lambda I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The continuous spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 are all those values 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\sigma\left(D\right)$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $D-\lambda I$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one but not onto, and the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $D-\lambda I$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Examples include the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost-eigenvectors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, i.e.
 vector-sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{n}$
\end_inset

 that converge to ever-smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(D-\lambda I\right)\vec{v}_{n}\to0$
\end_inset

, while at the same time not converging themselves: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\vec{v}_{n}\right|\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Such 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

's belong to the continuous spectrum, not the point spectrum.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The residual spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 are all those values 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\sigma\left(D\right)$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $D-\lambda I$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one but not onto, and the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $D-\lambda I$
\end_inset

 is not dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It would appear that 
\begin_inset Formula $D-\lambda I$
\end_inset

 has a point spectrum that is pretty much the entire complex plane.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 has a pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1$
\end_inset

 and so as 
\begin_inset Formula $s\to1$
\end_inset

 it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Whether or not the point spectrum really is the entire complex plane or
 not requires answering the question: does 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 attain every possible complex value, or not? (I do not know).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way of saying is: the spectral radius of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is infinite (unbounded) because 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 is unbounded as 
\begin_inset Formula $s\to1$
\end_inset

 (and the sequence sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{n}=n^{-s}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

-summable as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>1$
\end_inset

; that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}\in\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>1$
\end_inset

).
 Does 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 attain every possible complex value in the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>1$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that just because the the point spectrum might be the entire complex
 plane, this does not mean that the continuous and residual spectra are
 empty.
 These are distinct questions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Operator norm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What's the operator norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

? Let's try our luck.
 Consider the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}=\left(1,q,q^{2},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\vec{q}\right|=1/\left(1-\left|q\right|\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For the following exercise, it's pointless to imagine that 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is a complex number; so instead, take 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le q<1$
\end_inset

 real.
 The norm of the divisor operator applied to this vector is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|D\vec{q}\right|=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{q^{n-1}}{1-q^{n}}
\]

\end_inset

which is a Lambert series.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{1-q^{n}}\le\frac{1}{1-q}
\]

\end_inset

one can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\left|D\vec{q}\right|}{\left|\vec{q}\right|}= & \left(1-q\right)\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{q^{n-1}}{1-q^{n}}\\
\le & \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}q^{n-1}\\
= & \frac{1}{1-q}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is useless as a bound; it is no bound at all.
 Can we do better? It would seem that the asymptotic expansion 
\begin_inset Formula $q\to1$
\end_inset

 for the Lambert series is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{q^{n-1}}{1-q^{n}}=\frac{-\log\left(1-q\right)}{1-q}+\frac{\gamma}{1-q}-\frac{1}{2}\log\left(1-q\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(1-q\right)
\]

\end_inset

which implies that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\left|D\vec{q}\right|}{\left|\vec{q}\right|}= & \left(1-q\right)\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{q^{n-1}}{1-q^{n}}\\
= & -\log\left(1-q\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $q\to1$
\end_inset

.
 From this we can only conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is not a bounded operator.
 It's operator norm is divergent in this vector-direction.
\end_layout

