\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Dirichlet characters mod 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are completely multiplicative.
 Therefore, they too are eigenvectors.
 Given the character 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

, define the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\chi}=\chi\left(n\right)n^{-s}$
\end_inset

.
 The eigen-equation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D\vec{\chi}=L\left(s,\chi\right)\vec{\chi}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $L\left(s,\chi\right)$
\end_inset

 the usual Dirichlet 
\begin_inset Formula $L-$
\end_inset

series
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L\left(s,\chi\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{\chi\left(n\right)}{n^{s}}
\]

\end_inset

Just like 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\zeta}$
\end_inset

, the character vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\chi}\in\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\Re s$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 is always a root of unity or zero).
 Unlike 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

, which has no zeros for 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\Re s$
\end_inset

 , the Dirichlet 
\begin_inset Formula $L-$
\end_inset

series have zeros in the strip 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\Re s<1+\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 (Right? Am I imagining this? WTF?) This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 has a non-trivial kernel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An earlier section wrote down the matrix for 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-1}$
\end_inset

, which seems to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

obviously
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the inverse, by inspection.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 has a kernel in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

, one concludes that 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-1}$
\end_inset

 must be unbounded on 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 I presume (without checking) that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{L\left(s,\chi\right)}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{\left(\mu*\chi\right)\left(n\right)}{n^{s}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mu*\chi\right)$
\end_inset

 is the Dirichlet convolution.
